{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,320p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-factory/opportunity-matrix.json\"","aggregated_output":"{\n  \"opportunities\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Personal Task at Alarm Time\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"App Store: 'I need my morning task to appear at alarm time, not hunt for it' (34 mentions)\",\n        \"Reddit: r/productivity 'When alarm goes off, show me my actual task list' (29 mentions)\",\n        \"Competitor gap: Alarmy uses generic puzzles; no app connects to personal tasks\",\n        \"User workflow: Check phone → find task list → feel overwhelmed → snooze\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"30-90 seconds of attention at wake-up; users need to see actual task immediately or snooze and lose window\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Display top-priority task from Apple Reminders on alarm screen; dismiss snooze only by tapping 'Complete Task' button\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app that shows your actual morning goal instead of generic puzzle; bridges alarm + task manager gap\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Lightweight Accountability Without Shame\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"App Store: 'Social accountability works, but public posts feel extreme' (18 mentions)\",\n        \"Reddit: 'Accountability text to friend each morning; that works longer' (22 mentions)\",\n        \"Competitor feedback: I Can't Wake Up users report discomfort with public posts\",\n        \"User preference: Micro check-in (1x/week SMS) preferred to daily social posting\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Users benefit from external forcing but fear public embarrassment or judgment; need lightweight, private option\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Optional SMS/iMessage check-in to single contact (1x/week if enabled); user decides if accountability helps\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Only accountability model that is optional AND private; respects user choice without dark patterns\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Calendar-Aware Alarm Forcing\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Reddit: 'My alarm is fixed, but some mornings I have 6am meeting, other mornings 9am' (16 mentions)\",\n        \"Reddit: 'Google Calendar can trigger IFTTT, but can't trigger actual alarm' (no competitor solution found)\",\n        \"User workaround: Manually check calendar night before; set alarm differently\",\n        \"Design gap: iOS Calendar and Alarms are siloed; no bridge exists\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Fixed alarm time doesn't adapt to calendar; users rush some mornings, oversleep others; requires nightly manual check-in\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Post-MVP: Connect EventKit (read calendar); detect early meetings; offer optional 'early alarm' if needed\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app to integrate calendar urgency into wake forcing; data-informed alarm timing\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Snooze-Proof Task Re-presentation\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Complaint: 'Moved phone/scanned barcode but then just went back to bed' (friction alone insufficient, 24 mentions)\",\n        \"User observation: 'Each snooze shows time, but I forget the task' (implied in retention drop data)\",\n        \"Competitor behavior: Alarmy shows time on snooze, not task; users re-enter flow-state of sleeping\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"After snoozing, user forgets task context; no friction between snooze and wakefulness cycles\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Each time user snoozes, alarm screen re-displays task (not just time); haptic pulse reminder every snooze\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Task reinforcement on snooze cycle; most alarm apps show only time\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Friction + Purpose (vs. Friction Alone)\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Competitor analysis: SnoozeProof users report 'I just carried phone back and snoozed anyway'\",\n        \"Competitor analysis: Step Out of Bed users report 'Why do I need to go outside? No reason'\",\n        \"User feedback: 'Just need something to force me' + 'But friction without a goal doesn't work' (22 mentions)\",\n        \"Reddit: 'Would prefer task/accountability to location' (explicit preference for goal over arbitrary friction)\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Friction alone habituates within 2 weeks; brain learns to tolerate friction; needs meaningful purpose to sustain\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Combine friction (haptic + large button) with purpose (real task); task is goal, not side effect\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Alarmy has task forcing but with generic tasks; WakeTask has purposeful friction (YOUR tasks)\",\n      \"risk\": \"low\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Habituation Resistance via Refresh Mechanism\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Complaint: 'Works great until I get used to it' (21 mentions, all competitors)\",\n        \"Reddit: 'Novelty wears off; back to snoozing' (habituation is universal problem)\",\n        \"User workaround: 'Real money on the line; I show up' (financial stakes work but extreme)\",\n        \"Competitor pattern: Streaks, Alarmy, I Can't Wake Up all report 2-3 week retention cliff\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Effective techniques habituate quickly; users return to old patterns after 2-3 weeks; no sustained solution exists\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Post-MVP: Rotate task presentation (visual emphasis changes daily); optional micro-streak counter; swap task color palette every day to prevent visual habituation\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app to explicitly design for habituation resistance; requires user research post-MVP\",\n      \"risk\": \"high\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Free Core + Optional Stakes Model\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Competitor pricing: Alarmy $4.99/mo (users complain), Kiwake $6.99/mo (users avoid)\",\n        \"User request: 'Financial commitment works but app feels risky; wish it wasn't extreme' (18 mentions)\",\n        \"Competitor trust barrier: 'Don't trust startups with my payment info' (Nuj, Beeminder hesitation)\",\n        \"Market opportunity: Free core attracts casual users; optional stakes for power users\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Subscription fatigue; users avoid paid alarms; but some want financial stakes for motivation (mutual exclusion problem)\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Free core (alarm + task forcing); post-MVP: optional micro-stakes ($0.25/day if enabled) via trusted payment partner\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"Freemium model (vs. Alarmy's paid-first); optional stakes (vs. Nuj's mandatory); no subscription required\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Health Integration for Sleep-Aware Forcing\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Reddit: 'Sync with sleep duration; don't alarm if I slept <6h' (11 mentions)\",\n        \"Design pattern: iOS HealthKit integration possible but underutilized in alarm category\",\n        \"User request: 'Track woke first alarm as Health metric' (fitness tracking integration demand)\",\n        \"Privacy concern: 'Don't want to share wake time with unknown servers' (on-device only required)\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Fixed alarm ignores sleep quality; users may be sleep-deprived but forced awake anyway; opportunity to integrate health context\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Post-MVP: Read sleep duration from HealthKit (optional permission); skip alarm if sleep <6h and no urgent meeting\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app to use HealthKit for context-aware forcing; privacy-first (on-device only)\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Siri Shortcut Voice Task Entry\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Reddit: 'Voice task entry from bed/alarm clock' (24 mentions, top feature request)\",\n        \"Design gap: No alarm app currently supports Siri integration for task entry\",\n        \"User workflow: 'I use voice memo at night to tell myself what matters' (workaround shows demand)\",\n        \"Opportunity: Shortcuts app integration (iOS 15+) enables voice entry without app launch\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Users want to add tasks from bed without launching app; current workflow requires manual entry or app unlock\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Post-MVP: Siri Shortcut 'Add wake task: [task name]' → WakeTask processes + schedules for tomorrow\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app with voice entry integration; leverages Apple Shortcuts ecosystem\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Lock Screen Widget for Pre-Alarm Context\",\n      \"evidence\": [\n        \"Design pattern: iOS 16+ lock screen widgets enable persistent task visibility\",\n        \"Competitor gap: No alarm app currently uses lock screen widgets\",\n        \"User need: 'I check my phone first thing; wish task was visible without unlocking' (implied in task prioritization jobs)\",\n        \"Technical opportunity: WidgetKit + ActivityKit (iOS 16+) enables always-on display for iPhone 14 Pro\"\n      ],\n      \"user_pain\": \"Users must unlock phone to see task context; early-morning interaction friction adds delay\",\n      \"mvp_feature\": \"Post-MVP: Lock screen widget shows 'Alarm 6:30 • Write email to manager' (no unlock required)\",\n      \"differentiation\": \"First alarm app to use iOS 16+ lock screen widget; reduces friction to pre-alarm context awareness\",\n      \"risk\": \"medium\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_7","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Research Synthesis: WakeTask — Task-Driven Wake-Up Alarm & Accountability\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nWakeTask is a task-driven alarm app positioned between Apple Clock's simplicity and Alarmy's feature complexity. It forces morning task completion through deliberate interaction, optional lightweight accountability, and calendar-aware scheduling—addressing a 120-150K user gap of people who want their actual morning tasks at alarm time, not generic puzzles.\n\n---\n\n## Target User & Urgent Problem\n\n### Primary User: The Frustrated Morning Task Person\n- **Demographics**: 25-45, employed or studying, smartphone-dependent\n- **Context**: Works from home or has flexible start time; lost natural wake trigger\n- **Behavior**: Uses task manager (Todoist/Reminders) but abandons morning routine; hits snooze 3-4x daily\n- **Device Habits**: Phone within arm's reach at night; checks calendar and tasks first thing\n\n### Secondary Users (Segment Growth Opportunities)\n1. **Remote Workers** (9 mentions, Reddit): Lost commute friction; need artificial structure\n2. **Neurodivergent/ADHD Users** (22 mentions, Reddit): Willpower insufficient; need external forcing\n3. **Parents of Young Children** (9 mentions, Reddit): Pre-existing chaos; need 60-sec morning clarity before kids wake\n4. **Students/Flexible Schedule** (implied): Alarm time varies by day; need calendar-aware flexibility\n\n### Urgent Problem: The 30-Second Wake Trap\nUsers wake up with **30-90 seconds of attention budget** before sleep inertia recaptures them. In that window:\n- Apple Clock option: Just dismiss alarm (no task context)\n- Alarmy option: Solve math puzzle (generic, disconnected from actual morning)\n- Current workflow: Check phone, find task list, feel overwhelmed, snooze\n- **Gap**: No app connects alarm moment to actual morning task\n\n**Evidence**:\n- \"I need my morning task to appear at alarm time, not hunt for it\" (34 App Store + Reddit mentions)\n- \"Friction works but then I go back to bed anyway\" (24 mentions)\n- \"Works great until I get used to it\" (21 mentions)\n\n---\n\n## Jobs-to-be-Done\n\n### Primary Job: Get Out of Bed Reliably\n**Context**: Heavy sleeper who sets multiple alarms; snoozes regularly\n**Job Statement**: When I wake up, I need to get out of bed quickly so I can start my day on time and not feel rushed\n**Current Solution**: Setting 10 alarms (ineffective); depends on partner (not scalable)\n**Success Metric**: Rise on first or second alarm (<2 snoozes) 4+ days/week\n\n### Secondary Job: Prioritize Morning Ruthlessly\n**Context**: Overwhelmed by full task list at wake time\n**Job Statement**: When I wake up, I need to know my top 1-2 priorities instantly so I don't waste time deciding\n**Current Solution**: Bullet journal night before; sticky note on mirror\n**Success Metric**: Identify priorities in <30 seconds; complete top task in first 30 min\n\n### Tertiary Job: Build Sustainable Morning Habit\n**Context**: Apps work 2-3 weeks then novelty wears off\n**Job Statement**: When I want to maintain a morning routine, I need something that stays effective long-term so I don't revert to old patterns\n**Current Solution**: Financial stakes (Nuj, Beeminder) or accountability partner (text daily)\n**Success Metric**: 80%+ of mornings completing first task by week 4+\n\n### Quaternary Job: Feel Supported, Not Shamed\n**Context**: Struggles with willpower; tried social accountability but felt exposed\n**Job Statement**: When I'm struggling to wake up, I need accountability that helps without making me feel bad so I can sustain the habit\n**Current Solution**: Tell partner privately; avoid public social posting\n**Success Metric**: Optional check-in with trusted person (not public, not mandatory)\n\n---\n\n## Top Complaint Themes & Quoted Evidence Summaries\n\n### 1. Feature Bloat Dilutes Core (31 mentions)\n**Evidence**: \"Alarmy has games/music I don't want; just give me the task forcing\"\n**Root Cause**: Designers optimize for engagement/retention; users want single purpose\n**Implication**: WakeTask must ruthlessly exclude non-essential features (no music, no games, no social posting)\n\n### 2. Friction Alone Insufficient (24 mentions)\n**Evidence**: \"Moved phone/scanned barcode but then just went back to bed\"\n**Root Cause**: Friction without purpose fails; brain learns to tolerate friction\n**Implication**: Task forcing must be **purposeful friction** (actual morning goal, not arbitrary)\n\n### 3. Retention Drop After 2-3 Weeks (21 mentions)\n**Evidence**: \"Works great until I get used to it\"\n**Root Cause**: Psychological novelty wears off; no refresh mechanism\n**Implication**: Must support optional stakes/accountability that doesn't habituate (vs. gamified rewards)\n\n### 4. Social Features Feel Extreme (18 mentions)\n**Evidence**: \"Don't want to post to social media, but app only offers that\"\n**Root Cause**: I Can't Wake Up's model too exposed; users want micro-accountability instead\n**Implication**: Accountability must be optional, lightweight, and private (not public posts)\n\n### 5. Setup/Configuration Burden (15 mentions)\n**Evidence**: \"Apps require lots of setup before first alarm\"\n**Root Cause**: Power users want customization; casual users want zero-config\n**Implication**: MVP must work immediately (no configuration); advanced options in settings\n\n---\n\n## Competitor Strengths & Weaknesses\n\n### Alarmy: Strength in Task Forcing, Weakness in Purpose\n**Strengths**:\n- Proven task forcing works (245K reviews validates demand)\n- Multiple task types (choice perception)\n- Reliable alarm quality\n\n**Weaknesses**:\n- Generic tasks (math, puzzle, photo) disconnected from actual morning\n- Expensive ($4.99/mo = $60/year)\n- Feature bloat (games, music unused by users)\n- No accountability; solo forcing only\n- No integration with personal task systems\n\n**WakeTask Advantage**: Personal tasks + optional accountability + free\n\n### SnoozeProof: Strength in Simplicity, Weakness in Purpose\n**Strengths**:\n- Extremely simple; users adopt immediately\n- Growing (validates minimalist demand)\n- Friction-based forcing neuroscience-backed\n\n**Weaknesses**:\n- Friction alone insufficient; users return to bed\n- No task integration\n- No accountability\n- Growth plateau\n\n**WakeTask Advantage**: Friction + task purpose + accountability\n\n### I Can't Wake Up: Strength in Accountability, Weakness in Scope\n**Strengths**:\n- Social accountability validated as highest-impact\n- Real engagement signal\n\n**Weaknesses**:\n- Social posting too extreme for many users\n- No task integration\n- Habituation after 2 weeks\n- No calendar integration\n\n**WakeTask Advantage**: Optional micro-accountability + tasks + calendar\n\n### Nuj: Strength in Stakes, Weakness in Access\n**Strengths**:\n- Financial stakes most effective motivator\n- Real skin-in-game\n\n**Weaknesses**:\n- Trust barrier (payment in alarm app)\n- No task integration\n- Extreme for casual users\n- Micro user base (1.2K reviews)\n\n**WakeTask Advantage**: Optional lightweight stakes + free core + task integration\n\n---\n\n## Feature Opportunity Matrix\n\n| Opportunity | Evidence | User Pain | MVP Feature | Differentiation | Risk |\n|-------------|----------|-----------|-------------|-----------------|------|\n| **Personal Task at Alarm** | 34 mentions | \"Hunt for task list at wake\" | Show task from Reminders/custom list at alarm dismiss | First app combining alarm + personal tasks | Low |\n| **Lightweight Accountability** | 22 mentions | \"Social posting too extreme\" | Optional SMS/iMessage check-in to one person | Micro-accountability (not public) | Low |\n| **Calendar-Aware Forcing** | 16 mentions | \"Fixed alarm doesn't fit calendar\" | Task priority rises if meeting imminent; optional early alarm | First app integrating calendar urgency into alarm | Medium |\n| **Snooze-Proof Task Re-presentation** | 19 mentions | \"Forget task after snooze\" | Each snooze shows task again (not just time) | Task reminder on every snooze | Low |\n| **Lightweight Stakes** | 18 mentions | \"Financial commitment too extreme\" | Optional 1-min/morning streak or micro-stake ($0.25) | Stakes optional and low-cost | Medium |\n| **Health Integration** | 11 mentions | \"Don't wake if slept <6h\" | Skip alarm if sleep duration too low | Health-aware forcing | Medium |\n| **Habit Persistence** | 15 mentions | \"Tricks work 2-3 weeks\" | Rotate task presentation (visual/haptic/audio) | Refresh mechanism vs. habituation | High |\n\n---\n\n## Differentiation Thesis for App Store 4.3 Review\n\n### Core Thesis: Personal Tasks, Not Generic Games\nWakeTask is the first alarm app that forces you to interact with **your actual morning task**, not a puzzle designed by the developer. By connecting your personal task list (Reminders, Todoist, custom) directly to your alarm, WakeTask ensures the only way to dismiss snooze is to commit to what matters to you that morning.\n\n### Sub-Thesis #1: Accountability Without Shame\nOptional lightweight check-in with a trusted person (not public posts, not financial stakes). You decide if accountability helps you; it's never forced or exposed.\n\n### Sub-Thesis #2: Calendar-Aware & Context-Smart\nIf you have a 6am meeting tomorrow, WakeTask wakes you earlier. If your day is light, you can sleep longer. Calendar urgency shapes alarm behavior; alarm doesn't ignore your life.\n\n### Sub-Thesis #3: Free, Simple, Focused\nNo subscription for core features. No games, music, or social posting. Just the alarm, the task, and the accountability you choose. Built for people who already use Reminders/task managers; WakeTask is the bridge to actually doing them.\n\n### Why This Wins for App Store Review\n1. **Clear Differentiation**: Personal tasks vs. competitors' generic games/friction\n2. **Privacy-First**: On-device task storage; optional accountability; no tracking\n3. **Accessibility-Inclusive**: VoiceOver + haptic forcing for all abilities\n4. **No Dark Patterns**: Free core; no dark patterns; no manipulative gamification\n5. **Aligned with iOS Values**: Deep Calendar/Reminders integration; Health awareness; system-level design\n\n---\n\n## Design Direction\n\n### Alarm Screen UX\n- **Large task text** (40+ pt font, high contrast)\n- **One primary action**: \"Complete Task\" button (bright, unmissable)\n- **One secondary action**: \"Snooze 10 min\" (smaller, gray)\n- **Haptic feedback**: Strong, persistent pulse (Deaf accessibility)\n- **Minimal cognitive load**: Binary choice (Complete or Snooze); groggy user friendly\n\n### Task Selection (Setup)\n- **On launch**: \"Which app has your morning tasks?\"\n  - [ ] Apple Reminders (default)\n  - [ ] Todoist\n  - [ ] Custom list (WakeTask-managed)\n- **No complex setup**: Pick app, grant permission, done\n- **Dynamic task loading**: Each morning, pull top-priority task from chosen source\n\n### Accountability Option (Setup)\n- **Optional**: \"Do you want a check-in person?\"\n  - [ ] No (solo mode)\n  - [ ] Yes: Pick contact (SMS or iMessage weekly check-in)\n- **Lightweight**: Single check-in message once per week, if enabled\n\n### Lock Screen Widget (iOS 16+)\n- **Shows**: Alarm time + task name (e.g., \"6:30 • Write email to manager\")\n- **Tap action**: Launch WakeTask with task pre-selected\n\n### Gesture Interaction\n- **Swipe right**: Snooze 10 min (haptic feedback)\n- **Tap large button**: Complete task (3x haptic pulse; task marked done in Reminders)\n- **Force press** (if available): Quick task edit\n\n---\n\n## MVP Scope & Non-Goals\n\n### MVP Scope (Week 1-4)\n1. **Alarm Forcing**\n   - Set alarm time + recurrence (weekday/custom)\n   - Critical alert sound + haptic forcing\n   - Persistent notification until task completed or snooze selected\n\n2. **Task Integration**\n   - Connect to Apple Reminders (read-only)\n   - Pull top-priority task at alarm time\n   - Display task text on alarm screen (40+ pt font)\n\n3. **Snooze & Complete**\n   - Snooze action (10, 15, 30 min options)\n   - Complete action (marks task done in Reminders)\n   - Each snooze re-shows task (not just time)\n\n4. **Accessibility**\n   - VoiceOver support\n   - Haptic forcing for Deaf users\n   - Dynamic Type support (text resizing)\n   - High contrast dark mode\n\n5. **Settings**\n   - Alarm time + recurrence\n   - Snooze duration\n   - Task source (Reminders only, MVP)\n   - Haptic intensity\n\n### Post-MVP (Months 2-3)\n- [ ] Calendar integration (urgency awareness)\n- [ ] Lightweight accountability (SMS/iMessage check-in)\n- [ ] Todoist integration\n- [ ] Lock screen widget\n- [ ] Siri Shortcuts (voice task entry)\n\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,320p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json\"","aggregated_output":"{\n  \"appDir\": \"apps/waketask-iphone\",\n  \"appName\": \"WakeTask\",\n  \"bundleId\": \"com.keen.waketask\",\n  \"boilerplateRepo\": \"SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution\",\n  \"target\": \"TestFlight-ready iPhone app handoff\",\n  \"required\": [\n    \"research uses App Store reviews, Reddit, competitors, and iOS design references\",\n    \"spec candidates are generated independently and merged conservatively\",\n    \"Spec Kitty mission is recorded\",\n    \"SwiftAIBoilerplatePro is extended instead of rebuilding platform infrastructure\",\n    \"Swift 6 strict concurrency is preserved\",\n    \"production and test Swift files stay under 400 lines\",\n    \"SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, and secret scanning are wired as blocking gates\",\n    \"xcodebuild build and xcodebuild test run in the macOS lane\",\n    \"Appium/XCUITest exploratory tapper clicks every reachable enabled button/control\",\n    \"App Store 4.3 hardening checks release strings and metadata\",\n    \"Mobbin, if used, is pattern research only and credentials remain in environment variables\",\n    \"credential availability may be checked only as true/false presence; secret values must never be printed, logged, or written to artifacts\",\n    \"agents must not run environment dump commands such as env, printenv, set, export, or declare -x\",\n    \"final review fanout must approve product fidelity, iOS architecture, security, quality, QA, and release readiness\"\n  ],\n  \"forbidden\": [\n    \"hardcoded secrets\",\n    \"printing environment variables or credential values in logs\",\n    \"running env, printenv, set, export, declare -x, or echoing secret-like variables\",\n    \"writing API tokens, passwords, cookies, OAuth credentials, or base64 auth blobs to workflow artifacts\",\n    \"fake fixture-only research without marking the limitation\",\n    \"rebuilding auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, settings, or design system without ADR approval\",\n    \"declaring iOS validation complete without macOS or GitHub Actions evidence\",\n    \"skipping Appium exploratory evidence unless allow_macos_deferred is explicit\"\n  ]\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_10","type":"agent_message","text":"# Spec Candidate (GPT-5 Codex): WakeTask iPhone App\n\n## Problem Statement\nPeople who snooze through alarms lose a critical 30–90 second wake window. Existing options are either too passive (Clock), too generic (puzzle alarms), or too extreme (public shaming/financial pressure). Users need their real morning priority surfaced at alarm time, with just enough forcing to act.\n\n## Target User\n- Primary: 25–45 remote/hybrid workers or students who snooze often, use iPhone + task lists, and feel morning overwhelm.\n- Secondary:\n1. ADHD/neurodivergent users needing external structure.\n2. Parents needing immediate morning clarity.\n3. Flexible-schedule users whose urgency changes by day.\n\n## MVP Feature Set\n1. Alarm forcing core\n- Single active alarm schedule (time + recurrence).\n- Alarm UI with two actions: `Complete Task` and `Snooze`.\n- Persistent sound + haptics until one action is taken.\n\n2. Personal task at alarm time (differentiator)\n- Apple Reminders integration (permissioned).\n- Fetch top-priority morning task and display in large, high-contrast format.\n- On `Complete Task`, mark reminder complete.\n\n3. Snooze-proof task re-presentation\n- Snooze options: 10/15/30 min.\n- On every re-ring, task is shown again (not just clock time).\n\n4. Fast setup\n- Onboarding: choose task source (Reminders in MVP), grant permission, set alarm.\n- Time-to-first-alarm target: <90 seconds.\n\n5. Accessibility baseline\n- VoiceOver labels/actions.\n- Dynamic Type support.\n- High contrast support.\n- Haptic-only usability path.\n\n6. Settings\n- Alarm time/recurrence, snooze duration, haptic intensity, task source reconnect.\n\n## Non-Goals (MVP)\n- Public social posting.\n- Financial stakes/payments.\n- Todoist integration.\n- Calendar-aware auto-adjustments.\n- HealthKit sleep-aware suppression.\n- Lock Screen widget.\n- Gamified puzzles/music modes.\n- Multi-platform (watch/iPad/macOS).\n\n## User Journeys\n1. First-time setup\n- Open app → onboarding (value + permissions) → select Reminders list → set alarm → confirmation.\n\n2. Night-before planning\n- User creates/edits reminder in Apple Reminders.\n- WakeTask automatically uses top task for next alarm.\n\n3. Morning alarm flow\n- Alarm fires with task on screen.\n- User either taps `Complete Task` (marks done) or `Snooze`.\n- If snoozed, same task reappears at next alarm.\n\n4. Recovery flow\n- Permission revoked/network irrelevant (on-device).\n- App shows fallback message + local quick task entry for next alarm cycle.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n1. Task rendering\n- Given Reminders permission and an available task, when alarm fires, task text is visible within 1 second of alarm UI presentation.\n\n2. Complete action\n- Given displayed reminder task, tapping `Complete Task` marks it completed in Reminders within 3 seconds and stops alarm.\n\n3. Snooze cycle\n- Tapping snooze schedules next alarm at selected interval and re-displays same task context on next ring.\n\n4. Reliability\n- Alarm triggers when app is backgrounded/locked in at least 95% of internal test runs across supported iOS versions/devices.\n\n5. Accessibility\n- All alarm actions are reachable via VoiceOver rotor navigation.\n- Dynamic Type XXL does not clip primary actions.\n\n6. Performance\n- Cold launch to interactive home screen <2.5s on baseline test device.\n\n7. Code quality gates\n- Swift 6 strict concurrency clean.\n- SwiftLint/SwiftFormat/Qlty pass.\n- Production/test Swift files remain <400 lines each.\n\n## Analytics / Events\n(privacy-safe, no task content payloads)\n- `onboarding_started`\n- `permission_reminders_granted|denied`\n- `alarm_created`\n- `alarm_triggered`\n- `task_shown_at_alarm`\n- `alarm_completed_task`\n- `alarm_snoozed` (with interval bucket)\n- `alarm_dismiss_abandon` (if app exits mid-flow)\n- `settings_changed`\n- `permission_revoked_detected`\n- KPI rollups:\n1. First/second-alarm success rate.\n2. Snooze count per morning.\n3. 7-day retention.\n4. % alarms with successful task completion action.\n\n## Privacy & Security Requirements\n- On-device-first storage for alarm/task mapping and analytics queue.\n- Never log reminder text/content in telemetry.\n- No hardcoded secrets; no env var dumping in scripts/logs.\n- Principle of least privilege for Reminders permission.\n- Clear consent copy for data use and optional analytics.\n- Secret scanning enforced in CI.\n- Credential presence checks allowed only boolean-style (no values printed).\n- App Privacy Nutrition Label must reflect minimal collection.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Differentiation Statement\nWakeTask is not a clone alarm utility; it is a task-driven wake execution app. Core novelty is forcing interaction with a user’s actual morning task from Reminders at alarm time, plus snooze-cycle task re-presentation. Competitors focus on generic puzzles or friction tricks; WakeTask links wake behavior directly to personal intent, with minimalist design and no bloat features in MVP.\n\n## Appium Exploratory Testing Requirements\n- Automated exploratory tapper must traverse every reachable enabled control on core flows:\n1. Onboarding\n2. Alarm creation/edit\n3. Alarm ringing screen\n4. Snooze/complete flows\n5. Settings\n- Evidence artifacts required:\n1. Control coverage report (reachable enabled controls count).\n2. Session logs with timestamps.\n3. Screenshots for major states.\n- Fail criteria:\n1. Untappable enabled controls.\n2. Navigation dead-ends.\n3. Crash/hang during traversal.\n- Include at least one run per supported device class in CI macOS lane.\n\n## SwiftAIBoilerplatePro Module Reuse Plan\n1. Reuse platform modules as-is\n- App shell/navigation, settings framework, analytics pipeline, secure storage wrappers, networking abstraction, design tokens, test harness, CI scripts.\n\n2. Add WakeTask domain modules\n- `AlarmDomain` (entities/use-cases/scheduling abstractions)\n- `TaskIntegrationReminders` (EventKit/Reminders adapter)\n- `AlarmPresentation` (alarm screen + state machine)\n- `WakeTaskOnboarding` (permission and setup flow)\n\n3. Architecture constraints\n- Keep strict separation: domain vs adapters vs UI.\n- Preserve Swift 6 concurrency model (`Sendable`, actor isolation).\n- Do not rebuild auth/payments/storage infra without ADR approval.\n\n## Definition of Done\n1. Product\n- MVP feature set implemented and demoable end-to-end on iPhone.\n- Differentiation statement reflected in in-app copy and App Store metadata.\n\n2. Engineering quality\n- Build + tests pass in macOS lane via `xcodebuild build` and `xcodebuild test`.\n- Lint/format/quality/security gates green.\n- File size limits respected (<400 lines per Swift file).\n\n3. QA\n- Appium exploratory tap evidence attached.\n- Core acceptance criteria validated with test evidence.\n\n4. Release readiness\n- App Store 4.3 hardening checklist complete.\n- Privacy policy + permissions copy finalized.\n- TestFlight-ready artifact produced with release notes and known limitations."}}
